When you use `StoreWatchMixin` in different components, the updates are scoped to that component‚Äîthat is to say, change events for a watched store are handled once _per component_.

Consider the following quick-and-dirty example, which you can find running on JSFiddle at http://jsfiddle.net/BinaryMuse/1y1xc7yt/

``` javascript
var StoreA = fluxxor.createStore({
  actions: {
    "ADD_ONE": "handleAddOne"
  },

  initialize: function() {
    this.value = 0;
  },

  handleAddOne: function() {
    this.value++;
    this.emit("change");
  }
});

var StoreB = fluxxor.createStore({
  actions: {
    "MINUS_ONE": "handleMinusOne"
  },

  initialize: function() {
    this.value = 0;
  },

  handleMinusOne: function() {
    this.value--;
    this.emit("change");
  }
});

var flux = new fluxxor.Flux({store1: new StoreA(), store2: new StoreB()});

var App = React.createClass({
  mixins: [fluxxor.FluxMixin(React)],

  render: function() {
    return <div>
      <ComponentA />
      <ComponentB />
      <hr />
      <div>
        <button onClick={this.handlePlusClick}>Add One</button>
        <button onClick={this.handleMinusClick}>Minus One</button>
        <button onClick={this.handleBothClick}>Both at Once</button>
      </div>
    </div>;
  },

  handlePlusClick: function() {
    flux.dispatcher.dispatch({type: "ADD_ONE"});
  },

  handleMinusClick: function() {
    flux.dispatcher.dispatch({type: "MINUS_ONE"});
  },

  handleBothClick: function() {
    this.handlePlusClick();
    this.handleMinusClick();
  }
});

var ComponentA = React.createClass({
  mixins: [
    fluxxor.FluxMixin(React),
    fluxxor.StoreWatchMixin("store1", "store2")
  ],

  count: 0,

  getStateFromFlux: function() {
    this.count++;
    return {};
  },

  render: function() {
    console.log("ComponentA render");
    return <div>
      Component A - getStateFromFlux called {this.count} times
    </div>;
  }
});

var ComponentB = React.createClass({
  mixins: [
    fluxxor.FluxMixin(React),
    fluxxor.StoreWatchMixin("store2")
  ],

  count: 0,

  getStateFromFlux: function() {
    this.count++;
    return {};
  },

  render: function() {
    console.log("ComponentB render");
    return <div>
      Component B - getStateFromFlux called {this.count} times
    </div>;
  },
});

React.render(<App flux={flux} />, document.body);
```

The top component (`ComponentA`) listens to both stores; the bottom component (`ComponentB`) only listens to the second store (the one that updates via the "minus" event). Each time you click the "plus" button, the top component gets updated once. Each time you click the "minus" button, both the top and bottom components get updated, but each still only once.

Notice if you click the third button, which dispatches _both_ actions, that the top component is updated _twice_, while the bottom one is updated only once. This is because the top component is listening to both stores, and both stores emitted a change event, thus each event was handled separately. However, if you look for the `console.log` messages in your console, you'll see that this behavior is still only triggering one re-render, because React batches state updates together. As long as `getStateFromFlux` is fast, change events from multiple stores shouldn't be an issue.

